    "title": "World's First: India Makes Clean Hydrogen Using Nuclear Reactor Heat â€” Not Electricity",
    "summary": "India's Department of Atomic Energy has commissioned the world's first hydrogen production facility that uses nuclear heat instead of electricity. The copper-chlorine thermochemical plant at Kalpakkam splits water using heat from a fast breeder reactor, pointing to a round-the-clock, carbon-free route to green hydrogen.",
    "body": "\n# World's First: India Makes Clean Hydrogen Using Nuclear Reactor Heat â€” Not Electricity\n\n> **INCREDIBLE INDIA** — World's first nuclear-powered hydrogen plant\n\n## The World's First Nuclear-Powered Hydrogen Plant Is in India. Here's Why That Matters.\n\n**KALPAKKAM, Tamil Nadu** â€” For decades, the hydrogen economy has been trapped in a paradox. The fuel burns clean, but making it clean has been expensive and inefficient. Green hydrogen, produced by splitting water with renewable electricity, is weather-dependent. Grey hydrogen, made from natural gas, defeats the purpose. On June 26, 2026, India walked through a door no other country has opened. The Department of Atomic Energy (DAE) commissioned the world's first hydrogen production facility that replaces electricity with nuclear reactor heat â€” a Copper-Chlorine (Cu-Cl) thermochemical plant integrated with the Fast Breeder Test Reactor (FBTR) at the Indira Gandhi Centre for Atomic Research (IGCAR) in Kalpakkam, Tamil Nadu. Unlike every other hydrogen plant on the planet, this one does not use electrolysis. It does not burn fossil fuels. It uses the heat of a nuclear reactor to drive a sequence of chemical reactions that split water into hydrogen and oxygen â€” producing zero greenhouse gas emissions, operating 24 hours a day, independent of the weather.\n\n## The Problem: Hydrogen's Dirty Secret\n\nHydrogen is often called the fuel of the future. The International Energy Agency projects global hydrogen demand reaching 530 million tonnes by 2050, up from around 95 million tonnes today. It is essential for decarbonising industries where electrification is difficult or impossible â€” steelmaking, fertiliser production, oil refining, shipping, and aviation. But there is a catch. Nearly all hydrogen produced today comes from fossil fuels. Steam methane reforming â€” the dominant method â€” uses natural gas and releases roughly 10 tonnes of carbon dioxide for every tonne of hydrogen produced. That adds up to over 900 million tonnes of COâ‚‚ annually, comparable to the total emissions of Germany. Green hydrogen, produced via water electrolysis powered by solar or wind, avoids these emissions but introduces new problems. It is roughly two to three times more expensive than grey hydrogen. It depends on weather conditions. And it requires vast amounts of land for solar panels or wind turbines to generate the electricity needed for electrolysis. The world has been searching for a third path.\n\n## The Discovery: A Chemical Loop Driven by Nuclear Heat\n\nThe Cu-Cl thermochemical cycle â€” developed indigenously by the Bhabha Atomic Research Centre (BARC) in Mumbai â€” offers that third path. The process is elegant in its chemistry. Instead of using electricity to split water, it uses high-temperature heat to drive a closed-loop sequence of chemical reactions involving copper and chlorine compounds. Water goes in; hydrogen and oxygen come out. The copper and chlorine are recycled infinitely. The cycle operates at a maximum temperature of around 530Â°C â€” significantly lower than the 850Â°C or more required by alternative thermochemical cycles such as the sulfur-iodine process. The electrolysis step within the Cu-Cl cycle requires just 0.5 to 1.0 volts, less than half the voltage of conventional water electrolysis. What makes the Kalpakkam facility a world first is the source of that heat. The FBTR â€” India's only operational fast breeder test reactor â€” provides the process heat directly, bypassing the need to first convert heat to electricity and then use that electricity for electrolysis. This direct thermal pathway is inherently more efficient.\n\n## The Science: How It Works\n\nThe Cu-Cl thermochemical cycle involves four main steps: **Step 1 â€” Hydrogen Production:** Copper metal (Cu) reacts with dry hydrogen chloride (HCl) gas at 430â€“475Â°C, producing hydrogen gas (Hâ‚‚) and copper chloride (CuCl). **Step 2 â€” Hydrolysis:** Copper chloride reacts with superheated steam at around 400Â°C to form copper oxychloride (Cuâ‚‚OClâ‚‚), regenerating HCl gas for reuse. **Step 3 â€” Oxygen Production:** Copper oxychloride is heated to about 500Â°C using process heat from the FBTR, releasing oxygen gas (Oâ‚‚) and producing cuprous chloride (CuCl). **Step 4 â€” Electrochemical Regeneration:** Cuprous chloride undergoes low-voltage electrolysis at 0.5â€“1.0 volts to regenerate copper metal and copper chloride, completing the closed cycle. The entire process is continuous. Water is the net input. Hydrogen and oxygen are the net outputs. Heat â€” not fossil fuels, not electricity â€” drives the reaction. The only by-product is oxygen. Unlike solar or wind-based hydrogen production, which stops when the sun doesn't shine or the wind doesn't blow, this nuclear-powered system can operate around the clock, 365 days a year.\n\n## What's Next: From Demonstrator to Scale\n\nThe pilot plant is designed to validate the technology and generate the operational data needed for scale-up. Researchers at BARC and IGCAR will study the Cu-Cl process under continuous operating conditions, optimise reaction parameters, and identify engineering solutions for commercial deployment. The next phase involves integrating nuclear hydrogen production with advanced reactor systems now under development. The PFBR at Kalpakkam â€” India's first 500 MWe commercial fast breeder reactor â€” is nearing grid synchronisation after achieving first criticality in April 2026. Future fast reactors could potentially co-produce electricity and hydrogen, improving overall economics. Further ahead, FBTR-II â€” a 100-120 MWth advanced test reactor â€” is in the conceptual design phase, with green hydrogen production identified as one of its secondary objectives alongside isotope production and materials testing.\n\n## The Bigger Picture: Bhabha's Blueprint, 75 Years On\n\nThe Kalpakkam hydrogen facility is the latest expression of a vision that Homi Bhabha articulated in the 1950s. India's three-stage nuclear programme was designed to work around a fundamental constraint: the country possesses roughly 2 percent of the world's uranium but around 25 percent of its thorium reserves. Stage 1 â€” pressurised heavy water reactors using natural uranium â€” produces plutonium as a by-product. Stage 2 â€” fast breeder reactors like the FBTR â€” use that plutonium to breed more fuel and prepare the ground for Stage 3 â€” thorium-based reactors that would give India virtually unlimited clean energy from its abundant thorium reserves. The hydrogen facility expands this framework. It demonstrates that India's fast breeder reactors can produce not just electricity and bred fuel, but also industrial products essential for decarbonisation. It turns a 40-year-old test reactor into a multi-purpose clean energy platform. In doing so, it validates a broader proposition: that energy security, technological self-reliance, and climate action are not competing priorities. They are convergent â€” and India is proving it with hardware running on the Tamil Nadu coast.\n\n| Parameter | Value | Significance |\n|---|---|---|\n| Max temperature | 530°C | vs 850°C+ for S-I cycle |\n| Electrolysis voltage | 0.5–1V | vs 1.23V+ conventional |\n| Operation | 24/7 | Weather-independent, continuous |\n| FBTR experience | 40+ years | India's fast breeder expertise |\n\n",
